{
  "text": ". cellular circadian oscillations is based on autoregulatory 24-h transcriptional/translational feedback loops of a set of clock genes [CITATION_1] . The proteins BMAL1, CLOCK and its analog NPAS2 act as transcriptional activators via Ebox sequences driving the expression of clock controlled genes, some of them encoding other core clock protein repressors (PER and CRY). These PER and CRY proteins form complexes that are translocated into the nucleus where they shut down their own expression by removing the CLOCK(NPAS2)/BMAL1 complexes, defining a main negative loop. Some reinforcing loops are formed by the orphan nuclear receptors from the REV-ERB\u03b1-\u03b2 and ROR\u03b1-\u03b2 families, to modulate the rhythmic transcription of Bmal1, Npas and Clock [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Recent studies demonstrated that such oscillations in clock genes expression paralleled critical events of chromatin remodeling [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
  "correct_citation": {
